        <div class="textContainer">
            <h2>How To Install Windows 10 on a Chromebook</h2>
            <div class="information">
                <i style="font-size:24px;color:grey;" class="fa">&#xf017;</i>
                <p class="date">ㅤFri Feb 05 2021  ㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤAuthor: TheSonicMaster</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="content">
            <div class="text">
                <h4>
                    Let's see. ChromeOS is a bit of a dandy Operating System, especially if you were very used to Windows 10.
                    Let's turn your dreams into reality and make your Chromebook into a Windows machine. Before you do so,
                    special attributes towards <a href="https://mrchromebox.tech/">MrChromebox</a> and <a href="https://coolstar.org/">Coolstar</a>.
                    <br/>
                    We also need to make sure you are compatible so...
                    <br/>
                    - [You will need an Intel Processor] Open up crosh with <code>Ctrl+Alt+T</code> and type <code>uname -m</code>. If it returns with <b>x86_64</b>,
                      congratulations, you're compatible. Otherwise, sorry for the bummer (but you can always dual boot into
                      Linux if you prefer that).
                    <br/>
                    - You will also need 32GB or more storage. Windows itself is a behemoth of an operating system, taking up 20GB of storage
                      with additional apps and constant updates. If you have a 16GB Chromebook, sorry you can't do it.
                    <br/>
                    Make sure to check that your Chromebook is also listed on <a href="https://coolstar.org/chromebook/windows-install.html">Coolstar</a>
                    because they have the drivers for that Chromebook. If yours is not listed there, you can't run Windows 10 due to the drivers.
                    <br/><br/>
                </h4>
                <h>Heads up</h>
                <h4>
                  - Doing this will void your warranty, so you won't be able to ask for repairs.
                </h4>
                <h4>
                  - You will also lose all your Chrome OS files, data and applications that are not backed up. 
                  It is highly recommended you use Google's free 100GB Google Drive storage for Chromebook owners if you have a lot of files to back up.
                </h4>
                <h4>
                - A small screwdriver.

                - Another Windows computer (to create Windows installation media).

                - A USB flash drive of 8GB or larger (for Windows installation media).

                - A USB mouse during Windows installation - the built-in trackpad will not work (although we will install a driver for it afterwards).
                </h4>
            </div>
            <br/>
            <video width="1280" height="720" controls>
                <source src="https://www.chromebookmods.ml/public/images/zerobrane-ide/2021-02-02%2000-32-21%20(1).mp4" type="video/mp4">
            </video>
            <div class="text">
                <h4>
                    First install the script using this code for the terminal. <code>wget https://www.chromebookmods.ml/scripting/zerobrane-lua-ide-downloader.sh</code> 
                </h4>
            </div>
            <div class="image">
                <center>
                    <img src="https://www.chromebookmods.ml/public/images/zerobrane-ide/1.png">
                </center>
            </div>
            <br>
            <div class="text">
                <h4>
                    Next use the command <code>chmod u+x zerobrane-lua-ide-downloader-sh</code> to make it an executable
                    and then use the command <code>./zerobrane-lua-ide-downloader.sh</code> to run it.
                </h4>
            </div>
            <div class="image">
                <center>
                    <img src="https://www.chromebookmods.ml/public/images/zerobrane-ide/2.png">
                </center>
            </div>
            <div class="text">
                <h4>
                    Now type "y" and press enter and it will load up. In the screenshot I wrote "zbstudio" because 
                    I forgot to update the code, but it's updated now so you don't have to type "zbstudio" once you run
                    the script the first time. But if you want to run it after you installed it, you can run "zbstudio".
                </h4>
            </div>
            <div class="image">
                <center>
                    <img src="https://www.chromebookmods.ml/public/images/zerobrane-ide/3.png">
                </center>
            </div>
            <div class="text">
                <h4>
                    There you go, that's how you can use the IDE.
                </h4>
            </div>
            <div class="image">
                <center>
                    <img src="https://www.chromebookmods.ml/public/images/zerobrane-ide/4.png">
                </center>
